### BASHŌ

<span class="small">He lived at the close of the 17th century, and is
described by Professor Chamberlain as "acknowledged master of the
seventeen-syllable style," and his poems as "full of flashes of delicate
fancy," "specks of humour, truth and wisdom." He belonged to an ancient
Samurai family, retainers of the Daimio of Tsu-Isé. He became a Buddhist
priest, a student of the Zen doctrines, and was an artist as well as
poet. He took journeys into the secluded parts of Japan, and there
inscribed many poems on stones, some of which still remain.</span>

